history.content:
just take past eecs16a final exam and if you seems to understand it and know how to solve the most of the problems, then you are fine. 

otherwise if you aren't confident with circuit or some linear algebra, the previous eecs16a course website are very helpful because of the *recorded lectures and *notes!

It is not hard to find them on the websites, for example this semester's website is-- https://eecs16a.org/

and just go in and look for what you need! everything in 16a you need to know is there I think!

(advice from a student taking 16a this semester :)

children.subject: I'd also say that everything taught in eecs16a are very important and basic for the contents in 16B, so the more you feel you understand 16A's contents, the better you are prepared for 16B. And Miki(the professor) is the GOAT for this semester, I really appreciate his great teaching style and dedication!

Here's a condensed version of the notes a current 16B TA made https://eecs16a.org/EECS16ACompendiumOfNotesAndPracticeProblems.pdf. The 1st third of the class deals primarily with circuits but it gets linear algebra heavy afterwards. For linear algebra I'd say eigenvalues/eigenvectors, change of basis/diagonalization, least squares, is most important. For the circuits portion pretty much every topic is touched upon in 16B except maybe Thevenin & Norton equivalence.

I would watch circuit lectures from 16A when it either was taught by prof. vladimir stojanovic (Sp19 and Fa18) or gireeja ranade. They both teach really well and circuits only made sense to me after those lectures.
